{"parse":{"title":"Breaking Home Ties","pageid":8240460,"revid":848432571,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">This article is about the 1954 painting. For the 1890 painting, see <a href=\"/wiki/Thomas_Hovenden\" title=\"Thomas Hovenden\">Thomas Hovenden</a>.</div>\n<table class=\"infobox vevent\" style=\"width:22em;width: 22em; line-height: 1.4em; text-align: left; float:right;\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" class=\"summary\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;font-size: 125%; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic\">Breaking Home Ties<br /><small>(Boy and Father Sitting on Truck)</small></th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:BreakingHomeTies-NormanRockwell.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"BreakingHomeTies-NormanRockwell.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/c/c0/BreakingHomeTies-NormanRockwell.jpg/300px-BreakingHomeTies-NormanRockwell.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"306\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/c/c0/BreakingHomeTies-NormanRockwell.jpg 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"313\" data-file-height=\"319\" /></a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Artist</th><td class=\"attendee\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/Norman_Rockwell\" title=\"Norman Rockwell\">Norman Rockwell</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Year</th><td>\n1954</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Medium</th><td class=\"category\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/Oil_painting\" title=\"Oil painting\">Oil on canvas</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Dimensions</th><td>\n112&#160;cm&#32;\u00d7&#160;112&#160;cm&#32;(44&#160;in&#32;\u00d7&#160;44&#160;in)</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Location</th><td>\nPrivate collection</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><i><b>Breaking Home Ties</b></i> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Painting\" title=\"Painting\">painting</a> by American illustrator <a href=\"/wiki/Norman_Rockwell\" title=\"Norman Rockwell\">Norman Rockwell</a>, created for the September 25, 1954, cover of <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Saturday_Evening_Post\" title=\"The Saturday Evening Post\">The Saturday Evening Post</a></i>. The picture represents a father and son waiting for a train that will take the young man to the <a href=\"/wiki/State_university_system\" title=\"State university system\">state university</a>. The painting, considered by experts to be one of Rockwell's masterworks, is also one of the most widely reproduced, and was voted the second-most popular image in <i>Post</i> history.<sup id=\"cite_ref-vogel1_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-vogel1-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Description\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Description</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Finding_the_original\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Finding the original</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#2006_sale\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">2006 sale</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#Further_reading\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further reading</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Description\">Description</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Breaking_Home_Ties&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Description\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The details of the picture, as with most of Rockwell's works, combine to tell a story, in this case a story of endings and beginnings, as a boy from <a href=\"/wiki/New_Mexico\" title=\"New Mexico\">New Mexico</a> leaves home for the first time. The young man and his father sit on the running board of the family's stakesided farm truck. The ticket protruding from the son's pocket, and the single rail visible at the lower corner of the painting, by which the trio sit, suggest that they are at a <a href=\"/wiki/Whistle_stop\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Whistle stop\">whistle stop</a> waiting for the <a href=\"/wiki/Train\" title=\"Train\">train</a>.\n</p><p>The son's books are stacked on a new <a href=\"/wiki/Suitcase\" title=\"Suitcase\">suitcase</a> bearing a \"<a href=\"/wiki/State_university_system\" title=\"State university system\">State U</a>\" <a href=\"/wiki/Pennant_(sports)\" title=\"Pennant (sports)\">pennant</a>. With his tie and socks perfectly matched, wearing pressed white trousers and matching jacket, he is ready for his new life in <a href=\"/wiki/Higher_education_in_the_United_States\" title=\"Higher education in the United States\">college</a>. The young man's shoes are shined to a polished gleam, as, hands folded, and with the family dog resting his head in his lap, his gaze focuses eagerly toward the horizon, and on the next chapter in his life.\n</p><p>In contrast, the father sits slumped with both his and his son's hats clutched in his hand, as if reluctant to let him go. The direction of his gaze is opposite to his son's. The tag from a <a href=\"/wiki/Bull_Durham_Smoking_Tobacco\" title=\"Bull Durham Smoking Tobacco\">Bull Durham</a> tobacco satchel dangles, near at hand, from his shirt pocket. There is a red flag and a <a href=\"/wiki/Lantern\" title=\"Lantern\">lantern</a> at the ready, near his right hand, atop a well-used trunk. With the son's luggage unloaded and waiting next to them, there is nothing left for him to do but signal the train to stop, and his pose suggests that he is looking up the track, dreading the imminent arrival of the train that will carry his son away.\n</p><p>Though the two figures are not looking at each other, the sense of family ties is very strong in this iconic 1954 painting.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Breaking_Home_Ties&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The painting was shown in many locations over many years, including <a href=\"/wiki/Washington,_D.C.\" title=\"Washington, D.C.\">Washington, D.C.</a>'s <a href=\"/wiki/Corcoran_Gallery_of_Art\" title=\"Corcoran Gallery of Art\">Corcoran Gallery of Art</a> in 1955, and in <a href=\"/wiki/Moscow\" title=\"Moscow\">Moscow</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Cairo\" title=\"Cairo\">Cairo</a> in 1964. It was also the inspiration for an eponymous 1987 TV movie, featuring <a href=\"/wiki/Jason_Robards\" title=\"Jason Robards\">Jason Robards</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Doug_McKeon\" title=\"Doug McKeon\">Doug McKeon</a> as the father and son.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 2003, the painting was put on display at the <a href=\"/wiki/Norman_Rockwell_Museum\" title=\"Norman Rockwell Museum\">Norman Rockwell Museum</a>, which was its first public showing in over 25 years. Despite some experts noticing discrepancies between the painting on display and the published <i>Post</i> image, the painting on display was believed to be the original.<sup id=\"cite_ref-newport_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-newport-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Finding_the_original\">Finding the original</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Breaking_Home_Ties&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Finding the original\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>In 1962, the painting had been purchased for $900 by cartoonist <a href=\"/wiki/Don_Trachte\" title=\"Don Trachte\">Don Trachte</a>, a friend of Rockwell's, and was in his ownership until his death in May 2005. In March 2006, two of his sons found a hidden area in Trachte's house, which contained several paintings, including <i>Breaking Home Ties</i>. Further investigation found that Trachte had created copies of several paintings he owned, and hidden the originals, unknown to his family.  Thus, the <i>Breaking Home Ties</i> that had been put on display at the Norman Rockwell Museum in 2003, was actually a replica.<sup id=\"cite_ref-newport_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-newport-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The museum later placed the original on display, along with the replica.<sup id=\"cite_ref-vogel1_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-vogel1-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"2006_sale\">2006 sale</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Breaking_Home_Ties&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: 2006 sale\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>On November 29, 2006, <a href=\"/wiki/Sotheby%27s\" title=\"Sotheby&#39;s\">Sotheby's</a> sold the original painting at auction for $15.4 million, which at the time was a record sum paid for a Rockwell work. The buyer or buyers chose to remain anonymous.<sup id=\"cite_ref-vogel2_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-vogel2-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Breaking_Home_Ties&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-vogel1-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-vogel1_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-vogel1_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Vogel, Carol (April 6, 2006). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/06/arts/design/no-flattery-is-found-in-an-imitation-of-a-rockwell.html\">\"No Flattery Is Found in an Imitation of a Rockwell\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_New_York_Times\" title=\"The New York Times\">The New York Times</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">May 12,</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft.atitle=No+Flattery+Is+Found+in+an+Imitation+of+a+Rockwell&amp;rft.date=2006-04-06&amp;rft.aulast=Vogel&amp;rft.aufirst=Carol&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2006%2F04%2F06%2Farts%2Fdesign%2Fno-flattery-is-found-in-an-imitation-of-a-rockwell.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABreaking+Home+Ties\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0093647/\">\"Breaking Home Ties\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/IMDb\" title=\"IMDb\">IMDb</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">May 12,</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=IMDb&amp;rft.atitle=Breaking+Home+Ties&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.imdb.com%2Ftitle%2Ftt0093647%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABreaking+Home+Ties\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.newspapers.com/clip/10956544/rockwell_painting_is_films_inspiration/\">\"Rockwell painting is film's inspiration\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Burlington_Free_Press\" title=\"The Burlington Free Press\">The Burlington Free Press</a></i>. <a href=\"/wiki/Gannett_Company\" title=\"Gannett Company\">Gannett News Service</a>. October 10, 1987<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">May 12,</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Burlington+Free+Press&amp;rft.atitle=Rockwell+painting+is+film%27s+inspiration&amp;rft.date=1987-10-10&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newspapers.com%2Fclip%2F10956544%2Frockwell_painting_is_films_inspiration%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABreaking+Home+Ties\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-newport-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-newport_4-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-newport_4-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Flynn, Sean (June 11, 2016). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.newportri.com/newportdailynews/news/page_one/exhibit-explores-what-s-behind-the-walls/article_0d660ca7-70ee-5ecc-8581-61c2b2de28f1.html\">\"Exhibit explores what's behind the walls\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Newport_Daily_News\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Newport Daily News\">Newport Daily News</a></i>. <a href=\"/wiki/Newport,_Rhode_Island\" title=\"Newport, Rhode Island\">Newport, Rhode Island</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">May 12,</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Newport+Daily+News&amp;rft.atitle=Exhibit+explores+what%E2%80%99s+behind+the+walls&amp;rft.date=2016-06-11&amp;rft.aulast=Flynn&amp;rft.aufirst=Sean&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.newportri.com%2Fnewportdailynews%2Fnews%2Fpage_one%2Fexhibit-explores-what-s-behind-the-walls%2Farticle_0d660ca7-70ee-5ecc-8581-61c2b2de28f1.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABreaking+Home+Ties\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-vogel2-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-vogel2_5-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Vogel, Carol (November 30, 2006). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/30/nyregion/30rockwell.html\">\"$15.4 Million at Sotheby's for a Rockwell Found Hidden Behind a Wall\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_New_York_Times\" title=\"The New York Times\">The New York Times</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">April 2,</span> 2010</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft.atitle=%2415.4+Million+at+Sotheby%E2%80%99s+for+a+Rockwell+Found+Hidden+Behind+a+Wall&amp;rft.date=2006-11-30&amp;rft.aulast=Vogel&amp;rft.aufirst=Carol&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2006%2F11%2F30%2Fnyregion%2F30rockwell.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABreaking+Home+Ties\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Breaking_Home_Ties&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation web\"><a href=\"/wiki/John_Howard_Sanden\" title=\"John Howard Sanden\">Sanden, John Howard</a> (2006). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.worldofportraitpainting.com/commentary-sanden/rockwell.htm\">\"A Puzzling Mystery at The Norman Rockwell Museum\"</a>. <i>The World of Portrait Painting</i>. <q>What was a world-class museum doing showing an inferior replica, proclaiming it to be the original?</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=The+World+of+Portrait+Painting&amp;rft.atitle=A+Puzzling+Mystery+at+The+Norman+Rockwell+Museum&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.aulast=Sanden&amp;rft.aufirst=John+Howard&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.worldofportraitpainting.com%2Fcommentary-sanden%2Frockwell.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABreaking+Home+Ties\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation pressrelease\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20060929172915/http://www.nrm.org/page109\">\"An Iconic Norman Rockwell \u2013 Not Known to Have Been Missing \u2013 Found Again\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Norman_Rockwell_Museum\" title=\"Norman Rockwell Museum\">Norman Rockwell Museum</a></i> (Press release). April 6, 2006. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.nrm.org/page109\">the original</a> on September 29, 2006  &#8211; via archive.org. <q>Through an improbable convergence of circumstances, an iconic Norman Rockwell painting, not known to have been missing, has been found.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=An+Iconic+Norman+Rockwell+%E2%80%93+Not+Known+to+Have+Been+Missing+%E2%80%93+Found+Again&amp;rft.date=2006-04-06&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nrm.org%2Fpage109&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABreaking+Home+Ties\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation news\">Laughter, Shayne (May 8, 2017). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://indianapublicmedia.org/arts/breaking-home-ties-sketch-masterpiece/\">\"Breaking Home Ties \u2014 Prelude To A Masterpiece\"</a>. <i>indianapublicmedia.org</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">May 12,</span> 2017</span>. <q>For 40 years, the Indiana University School of Journalism displayed a charcoal sketch that the general public was never supposed to see.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=indianapublicmedia.org&amp;rft.atitle=Breaking+Home+Ties+%E2%80%94+Prelude+To+A+Masterpiece&a